<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Match Wine Weight to Salmon Preparation Method</strong> - The cooking technique dramatically affects which wines pair best with salmon. Grilled or blackened salmon's smoky char demands fuller-bodied reds like Côtes du Rhône or Oregon Pinot Noir, while poached salmon's delicate texture calls for lighter whites like Sancerre or Grüner Veltliner. The Maillard reaction from searing creates compounds that need wines with enough tannin structure to complement, not compete.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Consider Salmon Species for Optimal Wine Selection</strong> - King salmon's rich, buttery flesh pairs beautifully with oak-aged Chardonnay or white Burgundy, while leaner Atlantic salmon works better with crisp Albariño or Muscadet. Wild salmon's more pronounced flavor can handle bolder wines like Pinot Noir from Burgundy's Côte de Nuits, whereas farmed salmon's milder taste pairs best with subtle wines that won't overpower its delicate character.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Serve Whites at 45-50°F for Salmon Pairings</strong> - This slightly warmer temperature than typical white wine service (38-42°F) allows the wine's texture and mid-palate weight to better complement salmon's rich oils. Burgundian Chardonnay or aged Riesling at this temperature reveals more glycerol and body, creating a harmonious mouthfeel bridge with the fish's natural fats.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Choose Burgundy Glasses for Pinot Noir with Salmon</strong> - The wide bowl of a Burgundy glass concentrates the wine's delicate red fruit aromas while allowing them to meld with salmon's natural oils. This glassware enhances the wine's earthy undertones and silky tannins that make Pinot Noir the classic salmon companion, especially with herb-crusted preparations.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Avoid Over-Aged Wines with Delicate Salmon Dishes</strong> - Salmon's subtle flavors can be overwhelmed by wines with pronounced tertiary aromas. Skip that 15-year-old Barolo for cedar plank salmon; instead, choose wines 3-7 years old where primary fruit flavors still shine. A 5-year-old Sancerre or 4-year-old Oregon Pinot Noir provides complexity without masking the fish's natural sweetness.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Decant Young Reds 30 Minutes Before Serving with Salmon</strong> - Light reds like Beaujolais-Villages or young Burgundy benefit from brief aeration to soften any aggressive tannins that might clash with salmon's delicate proteins. This short decanting period opens up the wine's fruit character while maintaining the freshness that complements fish dishes.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Match Wine Acidity to Salmon's Sauce Components</strong> - Hollandaise or butter-based sauces require high-acid wines like Chablis or Saumur-Champigny to cut through richness, while citrus-glazed salmon pairs with wines having natural citrus notes like Vermentino or Vinho Verde. The wine's acidity should echo and enhance the dish's brightest flavors rather than compete with them.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Time Your Wine Service with Salmon's Temperature</strong> - Serve wine immediately as hot salmon hits the plate—the fish's warmth releases aromatic compounds that interact beautifully with wine volatiles. Cold salmon preparations like gravlax pair better with chilled wines served 10 minutes after plating, allowing the fish's cured flavors to settle and marry with the wine's bouquet.</li>
</ol>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I choose white or red wine with salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Both white and red wines can pair beautifully with salmon, depending on the preparation method. Light, crisp whites like Sauvignon Blanc or Albariño work best with poached or grilled salmon, while medium-bodied reds like Pinot Noir or Gamay complement cedar plank or blackened salmon preparations. The key is matching the wine's weight and intensity to the cooking method and seasonings used.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the best wine for grilled salmon with herbs?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Grilled salmon with herbs pairs exceptionally well with herbaceous wines that echo the seasoning profile. A Sancerre or Loire Valley Sauvignon Blanc offers complementary grassy notes, while a Vermentino from Sardinia provides Mediterranean herb characteristics. For red wine lovers, a Chinon or other Loire Cabernet Franc delivers herbal complexity without overwhelming the fish's delicate flavor.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Does the type of salmon affect wine pairing choices?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely – wild salmon's leaner texture and more pronounced flavor can handle fuller-bodied wines like Chardonnay or light Burgundy, while farm-raised salmon's higher fat content pairs beautifully with crisp, acidic wines that cut through the richness. King salmon's buttery texture calls for wines with good acidity like Chablis or German Riesling, whereas sockeye salmon's robust flavor can stand up to a light Pinot Noir.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine goes with salmon teriyaki or Asian-glazed preparations?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Asian-glazed salmon requires wines that complement both the fish and the sweet-savory sauce profile. Off-dry Riesling from Alsace or Germany provides the perfect balance of sweetness and acidity to match teriyaki glazes, while Gewürztraminer's spicy notes complement ginger and soy-based marinades. For a red option, try a fruit-forward Beaujolais-Villages that won't clash with the umami flavors.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are expensive wines necessary for salmon pairings?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Quality salmon pairings don't require breaking the bank – many excellent options exist under $25. Spanish Albariño, Portuguese Vinho Verde, or Oregon Pinot Gris offer exceptional value and complement salmon beautifully. The key is choosing wines with good acidity and appropriate body weight rather than focusing on price point, as salmon's delicate nature can be overwhelmed by overly complex or powerful wines regardless of cost.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What temperature should I serve wine with salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">White wines paired with salmon should be served at 45-50°F to preserve their crisp acidity and prevent the alcohol from becoming prominent against the delicate fish. Light red wines like Pinot Noir should be slightly chilled to 55-60°F, which enhances their fresh fruit character and prevents tannins from overwhelming the salmon. Serve wines 10-15 minutes after removing from the refrigerator for optimal temperature.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake when pairing wine with salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is choosing wines that are too powerful or tannic, which overwhelm salmon's delicate flavor profile. Heavy Cabernet Sauvignon or oaked Chardonnay can completely mask the fish's subtle taste, while wines with insufficient acidity fail to cleanse the palate between bites. Instead, focus on wines with bright acidity and medium body that complement rather than compete with the salmon's natural flavors.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can rosé wine work with salmon dishes?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Rosé is actually an excellent choice for salmon, offering the best of both worlds with white wine's freshness and subtle red fruit notes that complement the fish's flavor. Provence rosé or Sancerre rosé provide mineral-driven profiles that enhance grilled salmon, while slightly richer rosés from Bandol or Tavel work beautifully with salmon prepared with cream sauces. The wine's natural acidity and food-friendly nature make it incredibly versatile across different salmon preparations.</p>
